            <p class="mt-2 text-[0.88rem] leading-[1.6] text-muted-text">The synthetic SPL curve at the bottom uses procedural sine-modulation math, not actual acoustic radiation integrals. A real on-axis response includes: radiation impedance from the air load (which changes with frequency), the exact spatial integration of velocity over the cone surface weighted by Green's function, baffle diffraction, and the driver's electrical impedance interacting with the amplifier. The squiggles you see are qualitatively correct (peaks and dips grow past fb) but their exact dB values and frequencies are fabricated. For real response prediction, use a boundary element method (BEM) solver.</p>
